name: Marsha
description:
Please contact JoEllen (sagdinfo@gmail.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. **Meet our adorable Marsha!Marsha is a 3-year-old Schnauzer blend. She weighs approximately 12 pounds.Marsha was saved from a south Texas shelter where she was scheduled to be euthanized. She is a friendly girl that loves everyone she meets! She lives in a home with other foster dogs and enjoys playing with them. She is crate trained and housebreaking is progressing nicely.Marsha has been diagnosed with heartworm infection. Dogs acquire heartworm infections when they are bitten by a mosquito that was infected with heartworm larvae.Dogs with heartworm infection live happy, high quality lives as long as they are given appropriate care. Heartworm infection is relatively common in the United States, so we are in need of caring adopters like you that are willing to open their home to a dog with heartworm infection. We think that our heartworm dogs have just as much to offer their new adopters as any other dog and they deserve a chance at life.You are truly saving a life by adopting a heartworm positive dog! We provide all the medications to treat the heartworms to include 6-months of Advantage Multi® and 2-months of doxycycline.Her adoption fee is $200. This includes her spay surgery, DhPPv vaccination, rabies vaccination, deworming, 6-months of Advantage Multi®, microchip, leash and collar, Petco coupon book, and 30-days of pet health insurance.Please be aware that puppies and small breed do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m. Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@aol.com.

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and a 30-day trial of 24PetWatch Pet Insurance. Adopters will also receive a Petco Pet Parent Savings Books that contain:• $100s in savings plus a coupon for a free 6 lb. bag of WholeHearted dog food.• Thoughtful care tips.• Online resources and support.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time from the Austin area.

We do try to schedule bi-monthly meet-and-greets in Austin as interest is generated.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

name: Lovebug
description: Lovebug proved to be a perfectly fitting name as she is just the wiggliest, sweetest girl! And those big, puppy-dog eyes only make you fall in love with her further. Her foster mom lovingly calls her Snugglebug because she insists on getting as close to you as she can. Lovebug can be shy when meeting new people, but she warms up quickly and then will try to climb into your lap any chance she gets (even when you're standing!). She loves to be the center of attention, and she will let you know with a nose boop if she feels like you aren't giving her all of the attention she deserves. And if she falls asleep on her back, be ready to hear her snore! She also has very expressive ears, and they always let you how she is feeling. Now that she's feeling better, Lovebug likes to run and jump around, enjoys playing with stuffed animals and tug of war is her favorite game. For a two-year-old, Lovebug has already had a rough go at life. When she began experiencing hair loss, her previous family took her to a vet to get treated. Only a week after she was put on medication, the family surrendered her to their local shelter. A rescue partner of APA! reached out to us in an attempt to save Lovebug's life, and there were no questions asked. We scooped her up and delivered her into the arms of her current foster mom. Once Lovebug was in APA!'s care, the APA! Medical Triage & Wellness Clinic was able to determine that Lovebug was suffering from Demodex mange, which is the most common form of mange and is not contagious to other pets or to humans. Lovebug's fur is finally coming back in and she's more than ready to find her forever home. At 2 years-old, Lovebug still has a very puppyish personality, but she has excellent manners in the home - she's house-trained and does well being crated or left out to roam free while left home alone without any destructive tendencies. And she's done well with the small dogs she lives with. She's a goofy, kind and all around amazing young lady, and she can't wait to cuddle with you! Come meet this perfect pup!

name: Benito
description: When Benito looks at you with those giant saucer eyes, it's hard not to melt. His eyes are so pretty, we swear he must be sneaking on some eyeliner when nobody's looking. He has one adorably expressive ear and one stoic one, and between the two of them, you can always tell what Benito's thinking. And when he needs something, he gently paws at your knee to let you know. Benito has a real zest for life and loves to go on long walks and hikes and would likely make a great running partner. Benito also LOVES to play and tennis balls and rope toys are his favorite things. He loves to play fetch and even tosses the ball around for himself and has a collection of toys in his foster home that he's great at keeping himself entertained with. Benito does get pretty amped up during playtime, but once he gets it out of his system, he's relaxed and chill and happy to be a couch potato. As energetic as he is, Benito is the sweetest snuggler and likes to drape himself over your chest and snore softly. Benito learns commands very quickly and clearly wants to please his person. He's a very intuitive pup and seems to understand what's expected of him and obliges. If you want him to stop doing something, all you have to do is tell him and he instantly stops. He's ready to play when you feel like playing and stops on a dime when it's time to chill and lays his head in your lap. Benito wasn't crazy about kennel life and took it out on his bed and toys, but since spending time in his current foster home, he hasn't exhibited any of that destructive behavior. He's a completely different dog out of shelter and has transformed into a happy little mush-ball. He's fully house and crate-trained and goes into his crate easily and never makes a peep. Benito is friendly with meeting new people and may also do well with a doggie sibling that shares his rough and rowdy play style. He already knows 'sit', is working on 'drop' and learning all kinds of skills in APA!'s Total Obedience Program. The Total Obedience Program (TOP) is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Benito has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help him learn the skills to become the best dog he can be! Benito is learning skills like sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' coming when called and 'Place', which means he will go to a specific place in your home on command. Once Benito successfully completes all the skills on his training plan, he will be considered TOP Dog Ready! Benito is working hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Benito after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193 Benito would love to become part of an active household that will play with him to his heart's content. In return, he'll love you forever. Come meet this sweet pup!

name: Ace (referral)
description:
ACE (referral): CONTACT SANDY WITTLIFF, Trainer & Behavior Consultant at K9MUTT TRAINING, website WWW.K9MUTT.COM, email SWITTLIFF@HOT.RR.COM, phone 254-744-9926

Quick Stats
* Neutered Male; DOB 2012
* Current on Prevention & Vaccinations

I am Ace. I am a German Shepherd dog and right now I am at Fuzzy Friends Rescue in Waco, Texas. As with many GSDs, we don’t do well in kennel situations. So my friends are sending out some posts to see if there is someone that would like to meet me. I tend to be standoffish, and I am not a cuddle bug, but once we click I will be right there with you, watching your back and making sure you are OK. I just don’t like all that huggy stuff.  I do not like other dogs in my face. If they are in the same room we are fine. I just tend to be particular about my friends. I really would do better with a person who understands GSDs.  I need to be around adults . If I am around kids I am more comfortable around older ones.   I have been to obedience training and fun training of scent class. I was top in both my classes and can find anything. I love long rides in vehicles and walking, too.  I don’t pull but I do love to walk fast. I walk fine with other dogs just as long as we are not on top of each other.  

I am 6.5 years old; neutered; up to date on shots; on heartworm preventative; not crate trained, unknown with cats. See a You-tube video of me taking a ride:  https://youtu.be/CTWt3HEM6yI

name: Harper **courtesy listing**
description:
My name is Harper! I’m just over a year old and some sort of mixed-breed wire haired terrier, full of intelligence and fun. I weigh about 23 pounds soaking wet. Back in October of 2018 I got hit by a car out on 812 and was rescued and taken to the vet where my x-rays revealed no broken bones, just a bruised and cut noggin. 

A couple weeks later after I healed, I got all my rabies and parvo shots, and heart worm and flea preventatives. I have been spayed and don’t have any health issues or allergies, and I even chew my food like a lady!

Pet strangers don’t bother me, I just have to be introduced first. People strangers take a little more of an introduction, but once I know they’re not going to hurt me or my pack, I settle down and do just fine with them. If I can’t meet them, I just get anxious and won’t stop barking and growling because I want my pack to be safe!

Being a terrier, I am full of energy. When I’m bored, there’s nothing I like better than to chew on a good bone or treat ball (and the occasional shoe when I can’t find one of those). Outside is my favorite place to be. I need strenuous play for at least an hour every day, but I’d really like about double that. I get up early in the morning, usually around 6:00 AM and I’m ready to play right after I do my morning business. I love running, chasing flags, chasing balls, chasing other dogs, basically chasing anything because I LOVE to run and jump. I’m still trying to figure out how to play catch-the-frizbee, but in consolation I’ll let you know I’m really good at tackle-the-frizbee. 

Second only to playing, my favorite thing to do is sniff around while I wait for the humans to give me a job. They don’t know it yet, but I’d be great at a job where I could sniff around and pick things up and carry them. I bet I’d be great at a lot more than that, like learning tricks, but I do those things naturally. All I need is somebody who can give me the time to train me because my brain is always whirring and I just want to be working! I’ve started learning some commands like sit and stay so I know there is so much more I can learn and do. I’m just so excited to be alive and I want a human who can do as much for me as I’m going to do for him or her. 
Apply Here: www.bastropanimalrescue.orgInterested in adopting a pet from Bastrop Animal Rescue? To start the adoption process, please go to www.BastropAnimalRescue.org/adopt to complete an adoption application. Thank you!

name: Juanita
description: One of the first things you may notice about Juanita is her beautiful smile, not to mention her absolutely stunning silver eyes - pictures do not do them justice! And there are plenty of opportunities for Juanita to smile and flash those pretty eyes because she's a party girl with lots and lots of energy to burn. Juanita loves rope toys and giving smooches to her humans and should make the perfect running partner for the trail. This smart pup is also thriving in APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP), which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Juanita has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help her learn the skills to become the best dog she can be! She is learning skills like sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' coming when called and 'place', which means she will go to a specific place in your home on command. Once she successfully completes all the skills on her training plan, Juanita will be considered TOP Dog Ready! Juanita is working hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with her after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193 Juanita goes all out on anything you do with her, whether that be playing or learning new skills. One look from Juanita's eyes, and you'll be hooked. Come meet this amazing pup!

name: Sox JuM
description:
Sox JuM

I was named for my tiny little ankles socks that look like they are falling off or morphing into toe socks. Of if you are real sciencey and a chemistry buff, you can pretend I was named after the abbreviation for oxides of sulfur. But if that were the case, I would want to be named after my 3 favorite elements Barium (Ba), Cobalt (Co) and Nitrogen (N), because their acronyms spell BACON!!!

Science lesson over and more about me.  I am a BOY pair of socks, and that is the only pair I have left as per the neutering surgery. At 4 months old, I am full of puppy power, playfulness and kisses. I am a brindle and white Terrier mix and only weigh about 20 pounds right now and might only reach the low end of size medium.

My goofy ears periodically decide to go in diffurent directions, so if you need directions on how to get to the park, don’t ask me, it will be like asking the Scarecrow on wizard of oz and you might not get where you are going. I get where I am going by running and galloping.  I mostly go towards my friends, so that I can play wrastle mania.

I have lots of furry friends and sleep with a bunch of bunkmates. I do have some human friends too.  But I should tell you that I mostly like medium size and tall people.  Short people like kids make me nervous.

I am not sure about hobbits though, they are short but adults, so maybe I would like them???? To be on the safe side, Bilbo Baggins, do not apply for me, okay? I am ready to learn potty skills and I already know about walking on a leash. I hope you feel the chemistry between us and that you apply for me today!

GOD'S DOGS Rescue, in San Antonio TX, does not have a shelter - Our dogs are raised in foster homes in the San Antonio area. Each dog comes spayed or neutered, up-to-date with age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, heartworm tested and are current with monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. 

ALL OF THIS IS INCLUDED IN THE Local ADOPTION FEE OF $250.00 FOR PUPPIES and $200.00 for ADULTS. (Local is in the state of Texas). Medical records will come with each dog at the time of adoption.

IF THIS IS AN OUT OF STATE ADOPTION, TRANSPORT TO YOU is included in the adoption fee of $500.00 for PUPPIES and $400.00 for ADULTS. We transport all over the country!!

Our dogs are socialized, and we try to provide you a good understanding of the dog’s personality. Please contact us at info@godsdogsrescue.org for more information about adopting one of our dogs and puppies or fill out an adoption application at http://www.godsdogsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-application/ 

Please visit our website http://godsdogsrescue.org/ for helpful information re: transport, our adoption process and application, volunteering and fostering, and photos of our dogs/pups looking for homes!!

Thank you for wanting to adopt a rescued dog, their LIVES depend on it!

name: Jersey
description:
Happy Spring everyone! I have some good news to update everyone. I had another visit with the dogtor and had an ultrasound and biopsy. The results came back fairly positive. I do not have any cancerous cells, but the ultrasound did reveal some abnormalities in my liver and gall bladder. My liver is slightly swollen and gall bladder is retaining some sludge. Dogtor is not positive if the liver is causing the gall bladder problems or vice versa. I am now on medication for both and will go back to the vet in a month for another bile acid test to see if we have concurred my issues.I am definitely on the mend and really settling in with foster mom and dad. 
I had my first grooming on Thursday, and boy am I cute! If I don't say so myself. I was on my best behavior as my stylist made me look so pretty. I am looking forward to meeting a new family that wants to love and take care of me for the rest of my days. I have so much love to give!
Anxiously awaiting your application to adopt,
Jersey 
2/23/19 - Update
Hey everyone, Jersey here. I wanted to give you an update on my progress with foster mom and dad and my recent visits to the dogtor. I have decided that foster mom and dad are pretty fun. Foster dad brings me to work with him almost every day, so I am getting more comfortable in the car and love getting to spend the day with a lot of loving folks. I have been sharing my new home with a foster brother, Pepe the chihuahua, who seems to not mind my presence at all. We don't play, as I am still a little under the weather. I have definitely begun to show my personality more and have a little zip in my step now. I sleep so well through the night and have shown foster mom and dad that I am 100% potty trained. I have been to the vet a few times to try to figure out what is causing my awkward gait, and am getting closer to a diagnosis and treatment plan. The focus has been on my liver function, because some tests have pointed in that direction. It was confirmed this week that there is definitely something going on and I am scheduled for another test March 11th. I am hopeful that this test will pinpoint my illness and I can begin the road to recovery. I am a super loving pup that just wants to share my life with a super loving family. More updates to come after my next round of testing.
Howdy folks! My name is Jersey, but don’t let it fool you. I am not a northern girl, as I am proud to be a Texan. I am almost 9 years old and just under 8 pounds of lovable, sweet, Yorkie. I was recently surrendered to UYR by a savior that has tried to help me several times over my life. She wanted to provide a great home for me, but other puppies in the house occupied the only spaces her home would allow. So she did the next best thing and put me with new foster mom and dad. I have been here a week and am really settling in. I am a perfect southern young lady that is completely housebroken, a great snuggle buddy, loves other dogs, and sleeps through the night. I don’t bark at much and really love my two meals a day. I even like to observe things being cooked in the kitchen by foster mom and dad. I am not very fond of riding in the car or baths, but I will tolerate them.

I have been to the dogtor a few times last week to try to narrow down an issue I am having with my gait. I am fairly slow to get around, can appear a little dizzy at times,  and really can’t navigate any steps to and from the house. I also suffer from dry eye syndrome, but have medication that I have been taking for years  twice a day that keeps that in check. Dogtor has scheduled another test for me this week to get a better understanding of what is going on. Updates will follow.

I am looking for a forever home with a mom and dad that have a lot of time for me. I love to be on the couch with them, but need help getting up and down. Ideally my new parents will not have small children due to my size and lack of quick reflexes. I have a Texas size amount of love to give and want so badly to share that with my new parents.
label: not-adopted

name: Huey
description:
Huey was owned by a ranch hand who left the ranch and left Huey behind. When no one else at the ranch paid him much attention, Huey went wandering. For 4 months, he wandered a country neighborhood alone, following families on their walks with their dogs and playing with dogs along their fence lines, but was unwilling to let anyone catch him. He just didn't trust humans enough to let them come close.
 He spent both excruciatingly hot and freezing cold days laying out in the elements, in plain sight, but uncatchable. Animal control tried for 3 months. Neighbors tried to entice him into yards. The kind neighbors kept him fed, but he still wouldn't trust anyone. 
Finally a trapper stepped in and set a trap for him. A couple of days later, while checking the trap, the trapper was startled to look up and see him watching her. She watched him as he ambled by the trap location and down the street. She followed from a distance and found he had wandered into a neighbors fenced yard to play with her dog. A closed gate, snare, a can of vienna sausage snacks and an hour later, and he was on his way to a new life. 
At first, he flinched when touched, having forgotten the sensation. But with time and love he has tuned into a big, lovable baby who adores attention. He has no concept of his size and would prefer to be a lap dog. He is fairly low energy and is happy napping on the couch or outside in the sun. He walks well on a leash, but has a bit of fear about getting into the car that he is working on. He enjoys a hike at the park and a big yard to hang out in, but doesn't need a lot of high energy exercise to be happy. 
He is such a tall boy that he is a terrible counter surfer...he pretty much thinks that if it's close to the counter edge, you put it there for him. He loves toys, but mostly just carrying them around and trying to bury them in the yard. 
He enjoys other dogs, especially smaller ones. He might take a bit of an adjustment period with other large dogs, but he has become friends with every dog he has met eventually. 
He mostly sleeps on a dog bed, but once in awhile climbs up into bed to cuddle. He will chew on things you leave on the floor if you're not careful, but he's not a destructive chewer generally and does well left out at home unsupervised. 
He is not a fan of a kennel, but can be kenneled if necessary. 
Huey just needs love and a lifetime supply of dog chow to be happy. He'll even give you the biggest butt wiggles you have ever seen when you walk through the door. What more could a human ask for?

This super sweet girl is Jaime! She's a ~15 pound, 2 year old terrier blend who is on the quieter side and absolutely loves affection. She lets out an excited little whine when you go to pet her, her tail wagging away. She bonds tightly with her human family and gets along great with other dogs. She uses a doggy door at her foster home to go outside to potty. And she loves to play!
Jaime is heartworm negative. Her adoption fee is $175. This includes her spay surgery, DhPPv vaccination, rabies vaccination, deworming, heartworm prevention, microchip, leash and collar, Petco coupon book, and 30-days of pet health insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m. Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@aol.com.

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.

Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and a 30-day trial of 24PetWatch Pet Insurance. Adopters will also receive a Petco Pet Parent Savings Books that contain:• $100s in savings plus a coupon for a free 6 lb. bag of WholeHearted dog food.• Thoughtful care tips.• Online resources and support.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved and you are traveling from out-of-town, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time.

We do try to schedule bi-monthly meet-and-greets in Austin as interested is generated.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

name: Red
description: Heartworm Prevention is given on the 1st of each month If there's ever a dog that deserves a loving home, it would be Red. This poor pup came from a neglectful and abusive past, so we are searching for just the right family as his fur-ever home. While initially cautious towards strangers, Red adores his people. However, he can be fearful of men due to his previous experiences. He has never shown any aggressiveness and is always eager to please, so it doesn't take much to show this pup what you'd like for him to do. Gently corrections are the way to go with Red and his high food-motivation makes training much easier. He LOVES his kennel and you'll usually find him lounging in it with a squeaky toy or two (or all of them). Speaking of toys, Red has some resource guard issues, so gentle and patient correction is needed to show him he doesn't need to worry about his toys being taken. He also has a habit of sometimes taking other dog's food, so it would be best for him to be watched if he's fed with another dog or just fed separately. Red does wonderfully on a leash and greets other dogs and people in a friendly manner. He may do well in a home with one other dog, but slow and supervised intros are a must! While Red loves the company of his people, he doesn't seem to really care for playtime, as he'd rather just sit and contentedly chew on his squeaky toy next to you. While he may get along with other dogs and adults, he would do best in a home without other non-canine pets and children under the age of 10. Dog-savvy older children are welcome, as he will need lots of love, patience, and proper guidance from the whole family to help him flourish into the pup he was always meant to be. Are you that special someone that's the perfect match for this hard-knock-life pup?

name: Alexander
description: Alexander is a super lovebug who greets everyone with a smile. He loves giving hugs to his new human friends and seems to adore everyone he meets. It's not long before he's rolled over on his back looking for belly-rubs and then jumping up to show off his adorable zoomies. This playful guy loves to play catch and tug of war, and as much as Alexander loves toys, if there aren't any around, he'll entertain himself running around holding his own leash. While he's full of energy during playtime, Alexander is also well-mannered and knows when to chill out and settle for some cuddle time. It's times like these where he just seems to radiate calmness, sometimes finding a nice sunbeam to lay in and take a long siesta. At night Alexander loves to sleep with you or on his own bed where you'll be treated to his adorable (but soft) snoring. That's until you show him a toy - then he's up and ready to party! Alexander loves going for rides in the car and, very adorably, in a golf cart. He's also quite the waterbug and loves to run and splash in the water on a hot Summer day. We love how happy Alexander looks even when he's just rolling around on the grass to scratch his back or holding up his favorite toy between his paws to better admire it. Alexander has proven to be the perfect example of man's best friend in his foster home, and he recently became TOP Dog Ready! This means he has already learned all the skills in APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP), which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. Dogs in the program learn skills including sit and down, walking nicely on a leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers, calmly walking past another dog, staying in sit or down until told 'free', coming when called and 'place' which means Alexander will go to a specific place in your home on command. Alexander has worked hard to become a wonderful companion, and as part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193 Alexander's soulful eyes tell you he's grateful to be part of the APA! family but hopes to become a new addition to a home with new people and new toys to play with. Come meet this amazing pup! Follow Alexander on Instagram @doggiegohome_alexander

name: Denise
description: Rub my tummy!' Denise loves belly rubs, but she can't bring herself to 100% stop what she's doing to receive them. This results in the patented Denise Belly Bow, where she's half ready for love and half ready to play - she rolls over her front half for maximum belly rubs, while keeping her bottom in the air just in case she needs to break out in zoomies! Like all overgrown puppies, Denise loves her toys, especially the squeaky ones, and she's a big fan of playing fetch. She definitely has some energy to get out, especially first thing in the morning, but settles down quickly once she's had some exercise and then just wants to snuggle and get belly rubs. She gives good night and good morning kisses and will cuddle with you on the bed all night if you'll let her. She also sleeps upside down and smiling, just in case there's a belly rub she might miss while sleeping. And if you long to be greeted as if you've returned home from a 10 year odyssey every time you come back from HEB, Denise is your gal. She even sits on your feet to make extra sure you know you are loved. She'll follow you around the house wherever you go, including the kitchen where she'll politely asking for snacks with a very proper sit and those big beautiful eyes that are so hard to turn down. While Denise is definitely an enthusiastic pup, she's very eager to please her people, learns quickly and does great left alone - she's quiet, house-trained well-behaved and not destructive. Not sold yet? Then we should mention Denise's spots. She has secret spots that only appear when she's had a bath and her fur is wet! The perfect mix of playful and snuggly, whatever Denise does, she does it all the way. She'd love a home with an active family who will include her in their adventures and give her plenty of attention. If that sounds like yours, come meet this sweet girl!
label: adopted

name: CJ
description:
Up for adoption in Texas and New England: CJ. 





His current family adopted him from Lucky Lab as a puppy. Then he grew into a 70lb big, energetic puppy and they feel he's not quite the fit they expected.  CJ grew up to be 20lbs more than his mamma dog, who Lucky Lab saved from a shelter when she was pregnant. 





Here is what his current family says about CJ: 





CJ Stats:


Age - 13 3/4mos. (born 12/03/2017)


Weight - approx. 67lbs.





Likes:


Playing with Puppy Friends & Human Family


Being Outdoors


Playing in the Doggy Pool


Playing Chase and Hide-N-Seek


Playing Fetch


Running & Surveying the Land


Doggy Daycare with Friends


Eggs & Peanut Butter


Training Treats, Bully Sticks & Buffalo Horns!





Dislikes:





We had a difficult time finding anything he dislikes.  He would probably dislike being indoors all day but, we arranged our daily schedules to give him as much outdoor time as possible (and when we couldn't do that, we had him participate in doggy daycare for the day).





CJ is still kind of a big puppy who needs some more training.  He's a bit stubborn when you tell him to come back inside if he's playing outside.





He likes to naw on fluffy things like pillows and other stuff, but when you're a big puppy you need to be given proper toys and nylabones, etc. to chomp on. 





His family says they are choosing to rehome CJ because they think he'd do best with an active family who might even have another dog that he can play with, throw the ball and run around--  or he could go to dog daycare to play and burn off his energy. 





CJ enjoys running outside and playing so much when  he hasn't had enough time outside and/or playing, he tries to expend his energy indoors by running around, jumping on everyone/everything.





One of our Lucky Lab volunteers went over and spent some time with CJ and he said: 





He was very friendly to me, but constantly jumping on me for attention. He would jump up on my front, side, back, etc... He knows sit and lay down, but is not the most obedient about actually doing them for me (but did do it a number of times for me). 





Given his size, the jumping would be a problem with small to medium size children. 





Per the adopter, he does very well at doggie day camp and plays with all sizes of dogs with no problems.





He is reported to bark at dogs and people while walking, but mostly because he wants to go play with then. We walked him a couple blocks in mist/light rain, and we saw one postal employee filling a mailbox but he didn't react. No dogs on our walk so I could not observe/confirm reaction to dogs. 





He wears a gentle leader during walks and is okay with it, but doesn't like it being put on (was a little wrestling match but no aggression). Despite the gentle leader, he tended to walk with the leash fairly taught, staying at its limit without really dragging the male owner around.





He was non reactive to my petting any part of his body. He liked being touched, but was still wild and jumpy while I did it, never really settling down for long. 





I think he will do fine in any home that is willing to deal with 70 or so lbs of puppy energy. He needs better training especially as regards staying put and not jumping on people.





CJ might do super well in a puppy/young dog training class. Sounds like he wants to please, he just needs to have someone spend some time showing him direction and letting him burn off his energy.





We can't tell you how many young adult dogs Lucky Lab has saved from the shelter who ended up there because they were young and full of energy, ate someone's shoes, and needed some refinement :). If you aren't ready for that don't adopt a young dog! Period. 





If you're ready for a bundle of sweet, loving energy CJ is neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. 





Apply at www.luckylabrescue.com

name: Beryl
description: Beryl is a golden boy with a golden smile! If you're looking for a new best friend who will greet you with full-body wags and kisses, Beryl is your boy. He loves his people and it shows when he flops over for belly rubs. When he's not cuddling with his volunteer friends, he's busy working on all his TOP (Total Obedience Program) skills. As a TOP dog, Beryl has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help him learn the skills to become the best dog he can be! He's eager to please, and it shows when he's working with his trainer on a number of skills including walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' and coming when called. Watch his video and you'll see that he goes to his 'place' on command and will wait patiently until he hears the word 'free'. Before coming to the shelter, Beryl lived in a home for several years, where he learned to be potty trained and respectful of his surroundings. He's the perfect match for anyone who's looking for a dog that can easily assimilate into the home. He shows some promise in going home to another well-matched doggie sibling. And Beryl would love a home with a backyard where he can run around and get his sillies out! Perhaps his biggest selling point is his steadfast devotion to the people he loves. He may seem shy at first, but it won't take long to win him over! So what do you say? Are you ready for a new best friend who will reward you each and every day with unconditional love? Stop by and meet this Beryl of love! And as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Beryl after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193

name: Mr. Jones
description: Mr. Jones is somewhat of a mythical creature. It's as if several different breeds were mixed in a blender and out came this adorable, goofy, happy-go-lucky pup. With his distinctive, dare we say distinguished, good looks (note the charming underbite, super long legs, back hawk, antennae like left ear), he is sure to be the belle of the ball wherever he goes! But Mr. Jones is so much more than a uniquely handsome gentleman - he is friendly and affectionate and loves to nuzzle against your legs while being pet. He's also playful, but he's pretty mellow about it, and would make an excellent companion for life's adventures. A genuine people lover, Mr. Jones has made a big impression on several volunteer friends who look out for him and take him for field trips, walks on the trail, and help him practice being the best dog he can be until he finds his forever family. This smart pup is also learning all kinds of new skills in APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP), which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Mr. Jones has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help him learn the skills to become the best dog he can be! He is learning skills like sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' coming when called and 'place', which means he will go to a specific place in your home on command. Once he successfully completes all the skills on his training plan, Mr. Jones will be considered TOP Dog Ready! He is working hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Mr. Jones after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193 Mr. Jones has a lovable awkwardness about him that is sure to leave a big grin on your face! description:

This poor guy really needs to find out what a true "loving" home is because he has obviously been mistreated; at first he is very submissive and shy. We highly recommend that you enroll your dog in training classes.

name: Rufus
description: Rufus is like that goofy friend of yours who is always cracking you up and whose zest for life is contagious! Rufus is happy doing just about anything - whether that's zooming around the yard, chasing tennis balls, or lounging in mud puddles like the cutest little hippo you've ever seen. Once he gets a few zoomies out of the way, he's ready to lounge around and watch a Netflix marathon. But no matter what he's doing, he's doing it with a huge grin and a huge tongue hanging out! His big smile and his wiggly butt are hard to resist. Rufus walks great on leash. He will happily hang out in his crate, but most of the time he doesn't need it - he stays home alone loose in the apartment while his foster parents are at work. He doesn't get on the furniture and has learned to stay out of certain areas of the house, like the kitchen. He loves attention and is especially fond of men. Very laid back and affectionate, Rufus loves to lay close by his people and gently remind them that they should be scratching his belly. But he also enjoys his alone time and will lounge on his bed or look out the window quietly while his people do things around the house. He's so happy to see his people every time they come home, he can't help doing a couple zoomies before rolling over for belly rubs. His quirks include laying with his feet sticking straight out behind him from under his chubby rear end and he often has very exciting dreams and makes adorable little barking and howling noises. APA!'s favorite little hippo lives big and loves big. We can't wait for him to get into a home where his big love is reciprocated and where he gets all the snuggling he can handle. Come meet this goofy charmer today!

name: Billie Jean
description: Billie Jean was a stray who just rolled on up to someone's house like, 'Hello! You seem nice! We are friends now, yes?' Yes, they are friends and they're now helping her to find her forever family! Billie Jean loves getting attention in any form it comes in; cuddling, playing, pets. She loves all sorts of toys and playing fetch and tug of war. and she makes pig noises when she's really happy. Though Billie Jean is always up for some playtime, she is also good to snooze on the couch with you. She loves to get close and LOVES getting scratches. Billie Jean is the very definition of 'down for whatever.' Billie Jean is house-trained, naturally well-mannered and eager to please. She knows 'sit', 'stay' and is great on leash. She would love a yard to play in but mostly wants a family to love. She seems to have gone through a lot to get where she is, but she's not the slightest bit cynical about it. She'll just keep on smiling until she finds her forever home. Is it yours?

name: Asia (& Tyler)
description:
Quick Stats
* Spayed 60 pound Female; DOB estimated 2016-17
* House & Crate Trained
* Heartworm Positive, on slow-kill treatment 
* Current on Vaccinations; Microchipped 
* Good with other dogs and people
* Not tested with children, but very gentle
* OK with vet office cat, but further testing needed
* Must be adopted with Tyler

Asia is a lovely young lady in search of a forever home for herself and Tyler—the love of her life. They came to our rescue together and are very bonded to each other, so they must be adopted together. Both have good temperaments and get along well with other dogs and people. They are house- and crate-trained, with no accidents so far. Both were extremely thin, but are eating well and are almost to their correct weight. 

Both dogs are doing well on their slow-kill treatment for heart worms. We will provide slow-kill meds to the adopter until they are negative. Alternatively, the adopter can have them treated with a quicker method after adoption. If the adopter uses our approved vet and receives prior authorization from us, we will pay for the quicker method.

If you would love to give two sweet and beautiful babies a wonderful forever home, please apply!

name: Samson
description:
Quick Stats
* Neutered Male; DOB estimated 2017
* House & Crate Trained
* Heartworm Negative; Current on Vaccinations; Microchipped 
* Good with people
* Learning social skills with other dogs
* OK with vet office cat, but further testing needed
* Underweight

Samson is a handsome young boy in search of a forever home. Samson has EPI, a condition where he cannot absorb the nutrients from his food unless certain enzymes are added. It’s a lifelong condition, but easily managed once you get the right balance. The cost is about $50 a month. He is currently eating three times a day, but once he reaches his desired weight, he will be fine eating twice a day. Right now, he’s gaining weight and becoming healthier every day!

Before coming to our rescue, Samson had not been around other dogs much and did not have doggie social skills, but he’s improving daily. He would be fine with most dogs or as an only dog. He’s good with people, but we haven’t had him around kids yet. He was fine with the vet office cat, but further testing would be needed if he is going to live with one. As a bonus, this guy is a quick learner!

If you can provide a loving home for Samson, please apply today.

name: Etta
description:
Up for adoption in Texas and New England: Etta.


This beauty with incredible radar ears is one year old and weighs 40lbs. 





Look at those beautiful eyes and awesome ears!  This is Etta - she is an energetic, wiggly, playful dog and just over one year old.  She’s living in a house with a cat and two other dogs right now and gets along with all of them.  While submissive to other dogs, she does love to go rough and tumble at playtime. She is a bit nervous and excited around new people, but as soon as she gets comfortable, she is quite the cuddly companion on the sofa!





Etta is working on her leash skills right now, and will eagerly offer you a “sit” for attention and treats.  She is a quick learner thanks to how well she listens and how much she wants to please, along with that healthy love of treats!  Etta just wants to be near by as your constant companion. When she is not, she can sometimes become a bit lonely and run from window to window searching.  With that said, she seems to be getting less anxious as her confidence grows. Etta is currently eating her meals in her crate and sleeping in it at night, but she’s not too fond of the crate otherwise.  





Etta loves bones to gnaw on and stuffed animals to toss and carry around before de-stuffing them!  She's also becoming quite accomplished at fetching and will love to play with you and a tennis ball.  She is the sweetest dog, so expect lots of doggie kisses from her all of the time.  Etta is a lover!





Etta is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and housebroken too!

name: Ranger Mouse
description:
Ranger's Stats:
12 years old
5 lbs
Chihuahua

He may be an older gentleman, but he’s still very spry and full of life! He wags his whole body, not just his tail, and he’s pretty much in a state of perpetual wag when you’re petting him. He rubs his whole body on you and gives lots of kisses. He’s still able to jump on and off the couch and bed, and he’s completely housebroken. He gets along great with dogs of all sizes as well as cats. At less than 5 pounds, this little mouse has a BIG personality. He is on seizure medication, but he doesn’t let that get him down, and he hasn’t had a seizure since getting on the medication. After his dental, he only has one tooth left, but he’s able to eat soft food just fine. Do you have room in your heart for a little Ranger Mouse?

Ranger's $350 adoption fee includes his vet exam, vaccinations, worming, monthly heartworm and flea preventative, dental work, neuter, and microchip.

If you live in the Austin Area and are interested in adopting please go to www.forgottenfriendstx.org and fill out an application.

name: Lizard
description: Lizard is a lovable softy with a big ole head and beautiful brindle coloring. He's a very affectionate fella, and his sweet and goofy demeanor is sure to melt your heart. Lizard has been reported to be a wonderful houseguest on sleepovers with volunteers - he's house-trained and was left home alone uncrated without any issues. He really seems to appreciate the peace and quiet outside of the shelter and was happy to chill or follow his person around the house like an adorable shadow. Lizard has a low to medium energy level, but he's still quite an entertaining companion. He ADORES belly rubs and will roll over and squirm around hoping you'll scritch and scratch his whole body, and he does his silly squirm to show how happy he is just laying next to you in bed. Lizard is the consummate cuddlebug, and he seems his most content when he's relaxing with his person, leaning his big body against them while they watch tv. His floppy jowls are just the cutest, and he's a big fan of his peanut butter filled Kongs and really any sort of chew bone. When Lizard looks into your eyes he seems to be saying so much... 'I'm a good boy, I trust you, and thank you for loving me.' He really is a special guy who can't wait to meet his forever family and show what a great companion he'll be. Come meet him!

name: Lola
description: Lola is an absolute love bug who wants to show affection to everyone she meets. Even within her foster family (that consists of ten other dogs!), she gets along with everyone. She does well with cats, is good with the children she encounters when out on walks, and she's great when meeting strangers, especially if they have treats! In fact, there's no one this sweet girl doesn't get along with. Lola has faced some bumps along the road in life and is paralyzed from the waist down, but she has let none of it dampen her spirits or slow her down. She does beautifully in her wheelchair and loves getting out for adventuring (check out her videos). Then when she gets back home, she's happy to scoot around the house following you wherever you go. At night, Lola is happy to curl up in your lap and fall asleep. Although Lola is very adept at getting around in a home environment, flights of stairs would be an issue, so a home or apartment with no stairs or maybe 3 or 4 steps to get up\/down would be preferred. Low energy, low maintenance and as gentle as can be, if you're ready to get all the love you can handle, come meet this sweet princess!
label: adopted

name: Mesquite
description:
Hi, my name is Mesquite and I am looking for a family of my own.  I have been told it will help to tell you a little about myself, so here goes.
I love long walks on the beach, or on a hiking trail, or down a sidewalk, and —well, basically I love going anywhere, as long as I’m with my person!  I love to go on adventures, so if you like that too, I might be the dog for you!
But don’t worry!  I wouldn’t mind being a couch potato either, if all you’re looking for is someone to watch Netflix with.
One of my favorite games ever is to play chase –you know, where I run around with your favorite sock or my soft stuffed toy and you chase me?  I just think that’s the best!
I think my favorite thing ever though has GOT to be belly rubs!  I love them so much that I’ve even been known to flop down in the middle of a long walk just for the chance for a good belly rub!
The nice lady who takes care of me says I am quite a character.  I think that’s a good thing since I see that I often make her laugh!
Though I love every human I meet (big & small) I’m not really too sure about other animals.  (Cats are mean and dogs can be kind of scary!)   I’d really prefer to be your one and only.  Know what though?  That just means I have EXTRA love to give to my family!
So that’s about it.  I hope you might consider me as your next family member.  If you would like to meet me or just want to get more information on me just call 210-619-1980 or email info@homesforpets.org.

This pup can be adopted by going to our web site www.homesforpets.org and filling out one of our applications.

name: Tallulah
description:
Tallulah’s had a pretty rough ride getting ready for her forever family, but she’s ready now. She recently recovered from surgery to correct a seriously prolapsed uterus and she’s doing fine now. She is a lovely average sized female with a white coat and brown speckles everywhere. She has a docked tail, natural ears and beautiful honey colored eyes.

Tallulah is heartworm negative and fully vetted. She’s a medium energy girl who loves squeaky toys and kissing her people. She loved her bath and knows when the treat bag rattles. She is house, crate and leash trained. She lives in a house with large and small, old and young dogs, and a cat and she fit in seamlessly.  She was very underweight when she got to ABR, and she is protective of her food so she is fed by herself just so no one gets in trouble. So, if you’ve waited for a polka dot Boxer to fill out your family and give you kisses, Tallulah’s your girl.

name: Mylo (Courtesy Listing)
description:
Courtesy Posting: Mylo needs to be rehomed because of aggression towards a baby in his home. He's 12 years old. 
This dog is not with Small Chance Rescue, but a member of the public is trying to rehome him. Please contact Jenn at 903-357-0754 if you are interested in adopting him. Info from his owner below:

Mylo is great with dogs of all sizes, cats, rabbits... I’ve yet to find an animal he isn’t good with, he even plays well with a friend's crazy Min-Pin. He is not at all good with kids. He’s never been great with them and the older he’s gotten the worse he’s gotten. He does tend to snap when someone pets him and he he doesn’t want to or he’s done being touched, which is new since the baby was born. He hates being outside for too long, something I think is due to him basically being a grouchy old man. He has faked injury for attention right after the baby was born.... So obviously personality for days. He loves his kennel, we call it his house and at bedtime we tell him to get in his house and he settles for the night. He is extremely attached to me to the point of aggression. He won’t let anyone touch him if he’s sitting by me and will growl and bite if they try. Every time Levi (baby) cries, Mylo yelps like he’s been hurt. We’ve done everything anyone has suggested and then some to fix this, as he has always been that way, but nothing has helped and it’s gotten worse with the baby to the point of the attempted attack. He’s had a very good obviously spoiled life but it’s now to where we have to keep him and the baby safe, and finding a better home for Mylo seems to be the best option. He’s in amazing health, I can get his records from the vet, if needed. He loves riding in the car and just being with me. He loves being lap dog and gives kisses. He’s house broken, kennel trained, leash trained can sit stay and lay down.

name: Puppy Athena
description:
Up for adoption in Texas: Athena.





She is 12 weeks old and weighs 15lbs.  Athena had an accident when she was a puppy and had to have an eye removed but that does not slow her down! 





Athena is a very playful puppy. She loves playing with her stuffed Panda bear and Tiger. She can self entertain pretty well and goes potty either outside or on the pee pad 90% of the time. She prefers dry, crunchy dog food to the wet stuff (at least for now!) and loves playing with everyone and everything.  





She is still in the puppy bite everything stage and loves to chase your toes. We are working on that and she is starting to figure it out. She loves to play with the bigger dogs and watch what they do. She’s not been around cats before since I don’t have them. 





If you ignore her for too long, she will come over and give you a quick little puppy bark to remind you to play with her. 





Apply for her at www.luckylabrescue.com

name: z_Harris
description:
***COURTESY LISTING***
For more info about this dog, please contact person listed below.

Our adorable, funny, loving cattle dog mix needs a new home. We love him to pieces, but he doesn't get along with our cats. He's 3 years old and an exact 50/50 split between cattle dog/heeler and pittie. He'd be a wonderful companion for someone who works from home or has lots of free time to just hang out. His favorite activity is napping near his people, although he does enjoy a good walk. 

He's not particularly athletic, and has had both ACLs repaired over the last year (he won't have any further issues other than occasional soreness from over exertion). 

Harris would do well in a home with adults or a family with older kids, no cats or really little dogs. He gets along great with our older female dog, and he is really wonderful with puppies. He's indoor only, crate trained, and knows the obedience basics. 

We are charging $150 for him, to make sure he goes to a good home. For more info, contact marinamaxwell@gmail.com.

I LOVE: Literally everything! Treats - love em. Scratches - love em. Squeaky toys - oh yes, I definitely love those! 

I HAVE: A fun and exuberant personality! I am confident, playful and super affectionate. 

I GET ALONG WITH: Other dogs and every person I have met. Here at the Wags Ranch, I will be meeting new friends like donkeys, chickens and pigs and my trainers say that they expect I will love them as well.

name: Maggie
description: Maggie is a 5 years old, 56lb Lab\/Border Collie mix.  She likes walks, not pulling on the leash.  She is good with kids 15 years up who are respectful of dogs.  Maggie is very laid back, but has now begun to engage her dog foster-brother to play, which is great!  She sits for treats and takes them very gently.  She does know sit, drop it, and off, and is ready to learn more fun things.  She is initially very shy when meeting, but becomes more comfortable with time.  Trust is important for her.  What she likes the best are:  treats, car rides, walks, sleeping on the bed, other dogs, belly rubs, window duty from the top of the armchair, and couch lounging with her head on the armrest.  She feels more comfortable with men but eventually warms up to women and children.  She is not crate trained but is house trained.  Maggie is up to date on vaccinations and spay.  If you like larger dogs, she\u2019s the girl for you.

name: JINGER
description:
Hi there!  My name is JINGER.  What’s yours?  Nice to meet ya!  

Hey!  Before you get attached to me, read all the way to the bottom.  You will see that I am still in Houston, TX but I want to get OUT of Houston and OUT of Texas so I can have a really good life.  I want to see Texas in my rear view mirror. A nice person came along and took me in and, now, I am ready to hit the road to your house!  Uh, make that “our” house, OK?  I definitely need a house with a yard cuz I need room to run and romp! (You may see me listed in several cities looking for my new home.)

I am probably a Ridgeback/Lab mix, the vet says.  I am almost 5-years old and I weigh 50 pounds.  I have had all of my shots and have been spayed so I'm ready to go to my new home with YOU!  Those funny-looking 2-legged creatures said I’m also microchipped – whatever THAT is.  At any rate, I am fully vetted.  Is that anything close to petted?  I love to be petted!  

Wanna hear more about me?  I am crate-trained and house-trained and I know Sit, Shake and Lay Down.  I am a very loving girl.  I want to be your one and only.  Even though I get along with other dogs, my foster thinks it would be good for me to be an only dog.  I don't want to vie for your attention.  I just want to be ALL YOURS!

My foster mom loves me SO much that she only wants me to fly to my new home even if a pet transport truck was available.  See my adoption information below.

If you would like to take me home (and you know you do), please email doggydarlings12@gmail.com  and she can get me on my way to a new and loving home!  My adoption fee is $500 USD and includes my vetting, spaying, microchip, health certificate, travel crate AND transportation on United Airlines from Houston, TX to areas in the Northeast U. S., North Central U. S., Northwest U. S., and Canada and will be arranged by the rescue group.  (This is a courtesy posting.  Doggy Darlings is not the rescue I am with and my rescue is a 501c3 non-profit in good standing.)

name: Tucker Jimmy
description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let’s get you all matched up with a loving new “furever’ companion and friend. You’ll find the application on the “Available Dogs” page.
NOTE:

Adoptions to Texas residents only

.

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together).

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
Tucker Jimmy is a major sweetheart and very eager to please. He is a little timid and cautious but once he gets to know you, he will love you forever! He is crate trained and has come a long way on a leash. He knows the doggy door very well and is starting to learn what it is like to become part of a family.

His beautiful red coat and dazzling eyes will have you mesmerized!

If you would like to meet Tucker, fill out your application today!
Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our “How To Help” page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

name: Brock
description: Did you know we had a social media influencer in our midst? From the latest bridle coat to the 'in' on the floppiest ears, Brock knows he's the voice of his doggy generation! Like any good social media guru, Brock has his own hashtag #brockstar! Back in the day, you could see him hanging out in many a public place as the exemplary spokesdog of APA! Of course, Brock isn't all fluff. He understands the finer things in life - a soft bed, green grass to lounge in and nice strolls around the block. He knows all the ins and outs of living in a home and has been able to co-exist with chickens in the past and could also go home with a well-matched doggie sibling. He's also quite the 'Brockstar' when it comes down to his skills. He walks nicely on leash, sits and shakes on commands and has the sweetest flop into your lap when he's ready for snuggles. As a Canine Good Citizen trainee Brock enjoys learning new things where he works with a volunteer trainer several times a week toward the goal of passing the American Kennel Club's CGC test. To pass the CGC test, a dog must demonstrate obedience and general reliability in real world situations. Dogs in the CGC program learn to sit calmly when approached by strangers or another dog, how to greet people appropriately, stay in a sit or down until told 'free,' and come when called. Brock has been working hard to be a dog you can take anywhere with pride, and as part of APA's CGC program you can work with APA to continue to build a training relationship with him after adoption and get officially CGC certified for free! Check out a video about CGC: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193
label: not-adopted

name: Josie
description: Josie loves being around people and is so excited to see her friends at the shelter that when they enter her kennel, she walks circles around them, rubbing her face and body on their legs and then does these adorable little hops to show how happy she is to see them. As affectionate as she is, Josie doesn't give the big face kisses that make you scrunch your face. Instead, she'll get close, like she's sniffing you, and then daintily kisses your nose. Though Josie doesn't seem interested in playing with toys, whenever her friends at the shelter bring her a toy, she seems absolutely tickled and pleased that they've brought her a gift, like 'Oh, I can't use this right now, but thank you so much for thinking of me!' She walks wonderfully on leash, but is pretty low to medium energy and likes to sniff rather than go long distances. And she loves to roll around outside - not just in the grass, but also on the pavement, even if she's wearing a coat! But her favorite place in the world is definitely snuggled up next to you with her head in your lap. This good-natured young lady has really enjoyed playgroup in the past and be more than happy to go back to hanging with her canine buddies as soon as her knee is back to normal. She has an injured knee that needs surgery and is eager to find her loving home that will help her heal back to 100%. APA will handle her treatment, she just needs you to give her lots of love to help her recover. Josie can be a little shy at first with new people, but she'll be asking for pets by the end of the first meeting by rubbing her head and body against your legs and nudging your hand if you stop petting her, though with that irresistibly soft fur, that probably won't be an issue. This big cuddler loves affection more than treats, so much so, that when her trainers work with her, they primarily rewarding her with affection! She knows sit and is pretty good with recall and come, though it's hard to practice those, since Josie is kind of a velcro dog and wants to be by your side constantly! Josie is also APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP), which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Josie has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help her learn the skills to become the best dog she can be! Josie is learning skills like sit and down, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' coming when called and 'place', which means Josie will go to a specific place in your home on command. Once Josie successfully completes all the skills on her training plan, she will be considered TOP Dog Ready! Josie is working hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Josie after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193 Loving, sweet and low key, Josie would make a wonderful companion and she can't wait to daintily smother you in her love and precious kisses! Come meet her!

name: Dennis
description: Dennis is his name and smiling is his game! This compact little guy exudes happiness everywhere he goes. His tail wags nonstop when he's off on one of his mini adventures with his favorite human friends by his side. And don't let his senior status fool you - this boy loves to play! Whether he's chasing after tennis balls, roaming the ball fields or splashing in the pond, Dennis is having the time of his life! Perhaps his most favorite activity is crashing on the couch when volunteers take him home on sleepovers. He loves curling up in a little black ball and snoozing in front of the TV. So if you're looking for a cute little couch companion, Dennis is up for the job! Dennis has proved to be a model houseguest in the home. He knows to go outside when nature calls and he will only chew on his toys and busy bones. And now, after mastering a number of skills in his TOP Dog obedience classes, he is more than ready to move into a home where he can prove to be the best friend you could ever hope for! Dennis is working with a trainer on a customized plan on a weekly basis. In class he shows off his skills with great pride. He loves being the teacher's pet, especially if treats are involved! Dogs in APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP) learn skills including sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers, calmly walking past another dog, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' coming when called and 'Place', which means Dennis will go to a specific place in your home on command. Dennis has worked hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Dennis after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193 After a long day of work, Dennis loves nothing more than flopping down on a bed of soft sheets and rolling over for belly rubs with a silly grin on his face. So if you're looking for a fun-loving dog without all the muss and fuss, please visit Dennis today! He's more than ready to move into a loving forever home. You can follow his many adventures (and costume parties) on his Instagram page @adopt_dennis

Please be aware that puppies and small breeds do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m. Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@aol.com.

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.

Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and a 30-day trial of 24PetWatch Pet Insurance. Adopters will also receive a Petco Pet Parent Savings Books that contain:• $100s in savings plus a coupon for a free 6 lb. bag of WholeHearted dog food.• Thoughtful care tips.• Online resources and support.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved and you are traveling from out-of-town, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time.

We do try to schedule bi-monthly meet-and-greets in Austin as interested is generated.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

name: COSTA
description: Costa is a camo, colored cutie waiting for a home of her own. She\u2019s very curious outside the kennel, and she\u2019s excited to get out and sniff the playpen to see what amazing finds she could discover.  She takes her sniffing very seriously, and she has to finish her exploring before she turns her attention to other things, so she\u2019ll need a few minutes during introductions.  She\u2019s listed as a Plott Hound mix, but her ears suggest there\u2019s more involved than plotting. However, she does have other Plott Hound characteristics. She is alert to her surroundings. She\u2019s bold. When other dogs bark, she doesn\u2019t mind barking back. She\u2019s intelligent, and learns, quickly, plus she is gentle with people.  Speaking of people, Costa likes everyone she meets, and she\u2019s yet to meet a stranger. She hasn\u2019t met her new person yet, and she\u2019s ready for that to happen. Why don\u2019t you happen by and let this adorable girl introduce herself. You\u2019ll be totally charmed!

name: Mildred
description: Mildred recently gave birth to a litter of puppies, and now that they're off to their forever homes, she's looking for one of her own where she can continue to blossom. She's still figuring out how this whole beloved family dog thing works, and while she's not so playful with toys yet, since she probably never had any before, she's definitely curious about them. And she really likes the regular meals part of the deal. More than anything, Mildred wants to be loved and feel that she's safe. She's a sweet, gentle, submissive soul who loves nothing more than being by her person's side, getting as close as possible and looking at them with those adoring eyes, asking to be pet. She makes the perfect movie-watching buddy, and she loves meeting new people, since they always seem to want to pet her too. Despite not having any training, Mildred is incredibly well-behaved. She's house-trained and does great left alone outside of a crate. She's quiet, non-destructive and happy to nap in her bed until you get home. Mildred's a pretty low energy lady and walks perfectly on leash. She never pulls, and she's curious about any homes where she knows a dog lives. She's also done great with the dogs in her foster home. Mildred would make a wonderful addition to any number of loving homes that will let her know she's part of the family and include her on their adventures. If that sounds like yours, come meet this perfect pup!

name: Rustler
description: We've rustled up a good 'un here! Rustler is a handsome, healthy young adult who would love to settle in with a family where this fun dog will put a smile on everyone's face. Rustler is overall a pretty chill guy but he's ready for anything - a long walk or run, hanging out in the yard or even just some couch surfing. He doesn't need much and doesn't have an overly energetic demeanor that needs constant attention. He's just a cool guy who's very affectionate and loves to be with his people. He's got an ever-present bounce in his step that reflects his sunny outlook and just wants to be everyone's friend. Rustler is fantastic on a leash and doesn't get distracted by other people or dogs, as he keeps his focus on his walking partner. He is extremely obedient and behaves very well without a lot of management. He's lived in home before so he knows to follow the rules. Rustler also enjoys learning new things and is in the Total Obedience Program. The Total Obedience Program (TOP) is modelled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Rustler has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help him learn the skills to become the best dog he can be! He is learning skills like sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' and coming when called. Once Rustler successfully completes all the skills on his training plan he will be considered TOP Dog Ready! Rustler is working hard to become a wonderful pet, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with him after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https:\/\/vimeo.com\/89434193. Rustler's looking for a home where he can get some cuddle time and a soft place to lay his brindle head. Come meet him and see if he's right for yours!

name: Britta
description: Britta is a beautiful young pup who's already house-trained, sits like a champ, gives great eye contact and is eager to please her people. Britta is an incredibly smart girl and very serious about her training, and she will do just about anything for the good treats. She's a little aloof with new people, but after some high value treats and a game of 'fetch' (she's still working on the return part), she's ready for attention and loves to be scratched under the chin and told she's a good girl. Britta has an adorable way of chasing after the ball with her paws, never quite catching it on her first try and will bounce around after it forever. She also likes to play chase with her people and would likely make a great running buddy. Happy, fun-loving and full of energy, this sweet girl is looking for a home with an active person who will give her plenty of attention and include her on their adventures. If that sounds like you, come meet Britta!

Dogs in the CGC program learn to walk nicely on leash, sit calmly when approached by strangers or another dog, how to greet people appropriately, stay in a sit or down until told 'free,' and come when called. Bongo has been working hard to be a dog you can take anywhere with pride, and as part of APA's CGC program you can work with APA to continue to build a training relationship with him after adoption and get officially CGC certified for free!
